{"word":"νιν","slug":"νιν","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>νιν</b></el> <p/><div class='li750'><b>1. </b>doric and <b><a href='S:Tragic, in Tragic Greek'>Trag.</a></b> enclit. <a href='S:accusative'>acc.</a> of 3rd <a href='S:person, personal'>pers.</a> <a href='S:Pronoun'>Pron.</a>, like epic and ionic <el>μιν</el>, for <el>αὐτόν, αὐτήν</el>, <i>him, her</i>, <b><a href='S:Pindar'>Pind.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Tragic, in Tragic Greek'>Trag.</a></b>;—rarely for <el>αὐτό</el>, <i>it</i>, <b><a href='S:Pindar'>Pind.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>; and for <el>αὐτούς, -τάς</el> (in <a href='S:plural'>pl.</a>), <b><a href='S:Pindar'>Pind.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b>for <a href='S:dative'>dat.</a> <el>αὐτῷ</el>, <b><a href='S:Pindar'>Pind.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}